Quality of Service (QoS) in MQTT defines the reliability level of message delivery between the publisher and the subscriber. 
MQTT provides three QoS levels depending on how important the data is and the required reliability.

| QoS Level                 | Description                                                                    | Advantages                                      | Disadvantages                                                 |
| ------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------ | ----------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------- |
| **QoS 0 (At most once)**  | The message is sent only once without confirmation.                            | Fastest and lowest bandwidth usage.             | Message may be lost if the network fails.                     |
| **QoS 1 (At least once)** | The sender retransmits the message until it receives an acknowledgement.       | Reliable message delivery.                      | Duplicate messages may occur.                                 |
| **QoS 2 (Exactly once)**  | The message is delivered exactly one time using a four-step handshake process. | Highest reliability with no duplicate messages. | Highest bandwidth usage and increased communication overhead. |


Which QoS level is suitable for an IoT water level monitoring system?

For an IoT water level monitoring system, QoS 1 (At least once) is the most suitable choice.

This system requires reliable transmission of water level data to ensure timely alerts during rising water levels.
While duplicate messages may occasionally occur, they are generally acceptable because the latest sensor reading can replace previous values.
QoS 1 provides a good balance between reliability, network efficiency, and communication speed, making it suitable for real-time monitoring
applications.

Conclusion

QoS 0 is best for non-critical data, QoS 1 is ideal for most IoT monitoring systems, and QoS 2 is preferred only when duplicate messages
are unacceptable, such as in financial or transaction-based applications.
